Sticks & Stones
JAM artists protest The Nigger
Drawings exhibition, Artists
Space, New York, February 16-
March 10
Linda Goode Bryant and JAM regulars such as Janet
Olivia Henry, Howardena Pindell, and Lowery Stokes
Sims joined other art world figures, including Lucy
Lippard and May Stevens, to form the Emergency
Coalition in response to the infamous Nigger Drawings
exhibition at the nonprofit Artists Space, in SoHo, a solo
presentation of works by Donald Newman, a young white
artist. "Action Against Racism in the Arts," an essay the
Coalition would publish anonymously in the course
of the ensuing controversy, begins with a first-person
account that captures the significance the show's racist
title held for many artists, curators, and writers: "Almost
at once, the stench of southern jails, cocked guns, dog
bites, and the everpresent red-screaming cries of 'nigger'
were around me. The time was not 1962, however....
It was New York City, 1979, challenging the very exis-
tence of myself and other Blacks: challenging my very
existence as a human being."
The Coalition held teach-ins at JAM and protests
outside Artists Space." For its members, the exhibi-
tion was but one particularly egregious symptom of
a systemic problem: "Racial discrimination pervades
the whole of the art world, including publicly funded
'alternative' spaces," their text continued. "Even those
spaces created especially for minority artists are dis-
criminated against by being drastically underfunded.
The exhibition The Nigger Drawings points up this dis-
crimination: while the artist gets support for his show,
the art world fails to provide minority artists the oppor-
tunity to express and define themselves." This episode
highlighted the challenges spaces like JAM faced, and
made the gallery's relocation downtown, the epicenter
of the alternative art world, later in the year all the more
meaningful. -MI

JAM evicted from 50 West
Fifty-Seventh Street
Judson Realty sold 50 West Fifty-Seventh Street, and
the rent jumped from $400 to $1200 under the new
ownership, leading to JAM's first eviction." While Linda
Goode Bryant searched for a new home for the gallery,
Henry Korn, then executive director of the Lower Man-
hattan Cultural Council (LMCC), allowed JAM to oper-
ate out of the LMCC's offices at 32 Broadway, in the
Financial District.
